00:36:01,270 --> 00:36:01,949
Speaker 1: The one on the Xbox?

594
00:36:02,350 --> 00:36:02,687
Speaker 0: No, no, no.

595
00:36:02,750 --> 00:36:04,509
Speaker 0: The one that's on the DS.

596
00:36:06,495 --> 00:36:08,490
Speaker 0: Oh, yeah, that nanostray game.

597
00:36:08,731 --> 00:36:13,329
Speaker 0: I'm not sure if that has multiplayer, but I heard that the second one might have some multiplayer.

598
00:36:13,916 --> 00:36:14,730
Speaker 0: So, that's pretty cool.

599
00:36:14,850 --> 00:36:15,195
Speaker 1: Oh, go ahead.

600
00:36:16,512 --> 00:36:17,330
Speaker 1: I just remembered something.

601
00:36:17,771 --> 00:36:27,569
Speaker 0: A lot of older shmups have co-op play, which is also something interesting because back in those days, the only games with co-op play were beat-em-ups and shoot-em-ups, pretty much em-ups.

602
00:36:28,150 --> 00:36:33,870
Speaker 0: You would either, two people would walk down the street beating stuff up or two people would fly through space shooting bad guys together.

603
00:36:34,910 --> 00:36:39,410
Speaker 0: And as time went on, the co-op shmups kind of went away.

604
00:36:39,610 --> 00:36:41,490
Speaker 1: Well, co-op gaming kind of went away.

605
00:36:41,610 --> 00:36:44,148
Speaker 0: Yeah, now it's sort of back and coming back, but...

606
00:36:44,530 --> 00:36:50,848
Speaker 1: I think the Xbox has a lot to do with that because a lot of the best co-op gaming was always on the PC and now the Xbox and Xbox Live...

607
00:36:51,110 --> 00:36:55,129
Speaker 0: Co-op gaming was always on the NES, where the shmups and the beat-em-ups were.

608
00:36:55,951 --> 00:36:58,830
Speaker 0: And then the SNES not so much and the Genesis a little bit.

609
00:36:59,070 --> 00:37:03,530
Speaker 0: And then when you got to the N64 in the 3D days, the co-op gaming was pretty much gone.

610
00:37:03,890 --> 00:37:08,450
Speaker 1: Too many games became just that player one, player two, player one.

611
00:37:08,950 --> 00:37:19,170
Speaker 0: And then all the 3D games on the PlayStation and the N64 and stuff were all 3D games that had split-screen multiplayer, but no co-op action.

612
00:37:19,471 --> 00:37:28,190
Speaker 1: What I just remembered is, and I gotta remember the name of it, but at Otacon in the far left of the video game room, we saw a game that was like this versus shmup.

613
00:37:28,770 --> 00:37:34,669
Speaker 1: Kind of like those puzzle-y fond games, but you pick a cute little girl and you fly the cute little girls against each other.

614
00:37:35,130 --> 00:37:38,310
Speaker 1: And depending on how well you shmup, it puts bad guys on the other person's screen.

615
00:37:38,670 --> 00:37:47,050
Speaker 0: Yeah, you know how you play like a puzzle game against someone and when you do better, it puts more crap on the other person's screen.

616
00:37:47,070 --> 00:37:50,930
Speaker 1: You set up the combo and then you blow it off and then they get screwed unless they counter it and all that stuff.

617
00:37:51,111 --> 00:37:53,230
Speaker 1: It was that, but it was a shmup with cute girls.

618
00:37:53,974 --> 00:37:56,290
Speaker 0: You picked, it looked like witches, basically.

619
00:37:57,191 --> 00:37:59,758
Speaker 0: And you picked a witch.

620
00:37:59,778 --> 00:38:02,687
Speaker 0: and I guess depending on which witch you picked, yeah.

621
00:38:04,670 --> 00:38:08,708
Speaker 0: Depending on which witch you selected, it would send different bad guys over to the other side.

622
00:38:09,411 --> 00:38:17,630
Speaker 0: And you played a shmup on your side and the more bad guys you killed and the better you played, the harder it made it for the other person.

623
00:38:17,791 --> 00:38:22,266
Speaker 0: And if they cleared out the stuff that they got sent over, then it sent worse stuff over to you.

624
00:38:22,470 --> 00:38:25,910
Speaker 0: And it was pretty cool and I kind of wanted to play it, but there was a line.

625
00:38:26,250 --> 00:38:26,870
Speaker 1: There wasn't a line.

626
00:38:26,930 --> 00:38:31,469
Speaker 1: I was about to say we really wanted to play it, but there was just this guy sitting there playing it.

627
00:38:31,510 --> 00:38:32,606
Speaker 0: And there was another guy there, too.

628
00:38:33,250 --> 00:38:35,070
Speaker 1: There's two guys, but there was no one else.

629
00:38:35,111 --> 00:38:36,349
Speaker 1: And those two just kept playing it.

630
00:38:36,471 --> 00:38:37,510
Speaker 1: And eventually we walked away.

631
00:38:38,390 --> 00:38:44,130
Speaker 1: Thing is, though, that's a wider gripe I have about pretty much every convention other than the classic gaming at Katsucon.

632
00:38:44,851 --> 00:38:51,350
Speaker 1: It seems like there's really no enforcement of any sort of etiquette of, all right, let someone else play the goddamn game.

633
00:38:51,890 --> 00:39:02,010
Speaker 0: Well, the thing is, when you go to an arcade or if you're in a place with like relatively few games, there is sort of an etiquette about getting up from the game.

634
00:39:02,210 --> 00:39:06,170
Speaker 1: But no one follows that anymore, at least depending on what people do follow it.

635
00:39:06,230 --> 00:39:15,587
Speaker 0: The problem is, is that when you have a big convention, most people do follow the etiquette of, you know, you play a game, you know, maybe the loser walks in a fighting game or something like that.

636
00:39:16,551 --> 00:39:35,510
Speaker 0: But when you're at a big convention like that, right, the people who do not there are people out there who don't follow the etiquette, the type of people who will play a demo game for an hour and not leave it right at an anime convention or any other sort of gaming convention with, you know, some sort of shared console game that is publicly and freely playable.

637
00:39:36,191 --> 00:39:40,010
Speaker 0: Those are the types of people who are going to go to the game room and stay there a long time.

638
00:39:40,271 --> 00:39:43,508
Speaker 0: Also, the types of people who are going to sit down at a game and not get up.

639
00:39:44,410 --> 00:39:56,765
Speaker 0: And when you have a big convention and not so many games, odds are those kind of people, you know, if there's 100 of them at the con, they're all going to be sitting at a game system, taking it up.

640
00:39:57,252 --> 00:39:59,830
Speaker 1: Yeah, it doesn't help that those people tend to be oblivious to other people.

641
00:39:59,970 --> 00:40:04,589
Speaker 1: I just think cons what they need to do in the very least, because there are disagreements over what the etiquette is.

642
00:40:04,830 --> 00:40:10,490
Speaker 1: I mean, I've been to arcades where I put a quarter up to play DDR and someone stares at me like, what the fuck are you doing with that quarter?

643
00:40:11,150 --> 00:40:11,222
Speaker 0: Yep.

644
00:40:12,010 --> 00:40:14,430
Speaker 1: You got to just have rules posted somewhere.

645
00:40:14,732 --> 00:40:15,569
Speaker 1: You don't enforce them.

646
00:40:15,770 --> 00:40:17,669
Speaker 0: I found out the name of the versus Shmoop.

647
00:40:17,972 --> 00:40:18,629
Speaker 1: What's it called?

648
